snippet.textDisplay: Oh my god. A sportsman who values personal integrity over his ego or financial gain. He remembers what living under a dictatorship is like and as a proud Serbian he feels he must stand by his convictions. Meanwhile, Nadal has really disappointed me. He had no reason to make any comment about Djokovics' choice to refuse the vaccine and has benefited massively because of it. I wonder if he'll be quite so judgemental in a few years time when he realises the vaccines are useless, make no difference to transmission rates and barely anyone who isn't over 80 years old with one foot in the grave and Vit D deficient dies of Covid - not now and not from the get go. And meanwhile we are only just seeing the tip of the iceberg regarding long term damage from these vaccines. It seems every day more information comes out regarding how dodgy they are, that the science wasn't fixed it was fabricated and I predict a massive back pedalling by these vaccine nutters who at one point would probably have thought holding down people who refused the jab was perfectly reasonable. I don't know why but I have never believed this was a pandemic in the true sense. I have worked as a 1-1 carer for Covid + patients throughout this nonsense and after catching it before the 1st lockdown never tested positive again or fell sick. I'm probably the only person at my care agency who isn't vaccinated and strangely the only person who hasn't had to quarantine, stay at home sheilding relatives or called in sick for anything. I never wear my mask properly, rarely use the hand gel, hug any elderly resident who wants a hug (before I was banned from care homes) and generally ignore all Covid policies if humanely possible without getting myself sacked. I have been presenting the same LF test for months and not once has anyone noticed. Initially, I felt a bit like a social leper but now my bed wetting colleagues have nearly all accepted they were sold a pony. The ones who had the vaccine under duress because they were too poor to risk losing their job are furious - almost all regret not sticking it out. And the final irony - they all got Omicron apart from me (it's hard not to feel smug but I do try and rein it in). I have yet to personally witness any resident actually die from COVID as opposed to with Covid. Most people who die in care homes either have a fall and then die after catching chest infection or die of general neglect - poor diet/fluid intake, loneliness etc. If people hadn't been so easily fooled the majority of all funds could have been directed at care homes and relatives could've still visited - some of them are practically staff anyway and often spend hours sitting with their family member, feeding them and making sure they have enough to drink. A very time consuming job - so our government not only denied these poor souls the company of loved ones, they effectively cut staffing levels and that was before the mandate. But the public thought they were doing their collective best to protect these people, patting themselves on the back for wearing a useless mask and following useless arrows around the shops - someone, somewhere was surely laughing they're heads off.

snippet.textDisplay:
This is an extremely good piece of journalism in my opinion, but as an Australian I don't think it gets the reasons for the deportation totally correct.

I would say the decision was entirely political. The federal government realised public opinion was very much in favour of booting him out of the country, so that is what they did. The administrative and legal processes were handled very badly, but ultimately, there is no right of entry for foreigners into the country and the government has absolute discretion to deny entry to anyone for any reason.

The more interesting question is why the general public became so hostile to him being here. 
That starts with the fact that the population is unwilling to endanger how much better we have handled Covid than most other countries. For example, the number of deaths here per million of population is under 200, while in the US that is over 2800, and in the UK it is over 2400.

And then there's the fact that vaccination rates here are among the highest in the world. Currently, more than 95% of those 12-and-over have had at least one shot. There will be over 95% fully vaccinated soon, as most of those with only one shot are between 12 and 15 years old and waiting for 3 months after the first before their eligible for the second. 

I'd suggest that a lot of us thought that Djokovic's unwillingness to be vaccinated was sufficient reason to deny him entry here. For others it was his flouting of rules intended to protect others from Covid that became more than they were willing to tolerate. Going out and mixing with others, twice, and without a mask, while waiting for the results of a test is completely unacceptable behaviour. Then there was getting his travel details wrong on a health questionnaire he provided on arrival. He blamed his team for making a mistake, but most of is would think he'd have made sure he got this right if he actually cared about how his conduct affects others.
 
Personally, I hope he is never allowed back in, not just for the next three years. I think the evidence uncovered by Der Spiegel is quite compelling that his test results were fabricated! Why did he even bother applying for a visa in November when he was clearly ineligible to enter the country while unvaccinated? I don't believe it was a coincidence that he was "lucky" enough to get infected at the exact time he needed to qualify to enter unvaccinated.

snippet.textDisplay:
Saying his medical exemption applied to a "rule" is a bit of a stretch. ATAGI doesn't set ABF policy and the intention is still that anyone medically able to be vaccinated, is vaccinated. Recent infection doesn't excuse him from not being vaccinated in the past year. Djokovic would have had to prove he was medically unable to take the vaccine *at all*.

Edit: Djokovic's final appeal wasn't held in front of judge kelly. It was held in front of 3 federal judges, skipping out the review by a single judge and forfeiting djokovic's chances at any further appeals in order to expedite the process. The lack of full research on this is annoying.

How courageous. Exposing vulnerable members of the community to potentially fatal disease is a price he is willing to pay so that he can feel safe and risk losing additional millions to his current 220 million dollar bank account.  

Such fantastic awareness and priority of his personal health and wellness, while giving zero f*cks about the consequences for other vulnerable and less privileged people. 

POS. Should be in prison.

1. He tried to breach entry rules at the border. 

On his Travel Declaration form — which formed part of court documents released on Monday — the 20-time major champion ticked a box saying he had not travelled, and was not planning to travel, in the 14 days prior to his flight Down Under.

A statement on the form reads: “Note: Giving false or misleading information is a serious offence. You may also be liable to a civil penalty for giving false or misleading information.”

On its website, the Home Affairs Department warns that giving false or misleading information to the government is “a serious offence” carrying a possible jail term.

“If convicted, the maximum penalty is imprisonment for 12 months,” it says.

Djokovic flew from Spain to Dubai on January 4, then boarded a flight from Dubai to Melbourne on January 5.

On December 25, Serbian handball player Petar Djordjic posted a photo alongside Djokovic on Instagram, writing: “ONE AND ONLY!!!!! Thank you for the picture and for the nice wishes.”

2. He failed to comply with the rules that to enter Australia that you either have to be vaccinated or you have to have a valid medical exemption and show evidence of it. Djokovic’s medical exemption also wasn’t valid 

3. He may pose a health risk to the Australian community because allowing him to breach these rules may foster anti-vaccination sentiment. 

The immigration minister used powers under section 133C(3) of the Migration Act to cancel Djokovic’s visa “on health and good order grounds, on the basis that it was in the public interest to do so”.

On his Travel Declaration form — which formed part of court documents released on Monday — the 20-time major champion ticked a box saying he had not travelled, and was not planning to travel, in the 14 days prior to his flight Down Under.

A statement on the form reads: “Note: Giving false or misleading information is a serious offence. You may also be liable to a civil penalty for giving false or misleading information.”

On its website, the Home Affairs Department warns that giving false or misleading information to the government is “a serious offence” carrying a possible jail term.

“If convicted, the maximum penalty is imprisonment for 12 months,” it says.

Djokovic flew from Spain to Dubai on January 4, then boarded a flight from Dubai to Melbourne on January 5.

On December 25, Serbian handball player Petar Djordjic posted a photo alongside Djokovic on Instagram, writing: “ONE AND ONLY!!!!! Thank you for the picture and for the nice wishes.”

2. He failed to comply with the rules that to enter Australia that you either have to be vaccinated or you have to have a valid medical exemption and show evidence of it. Djokovic’s medical exemption also wasn’t valid 

3. He may pose a health risk to the Australian community because allowing him to breach these rules may foster anti-vaccination sentiment. 

The immigration minister used powers under section 133C(3) of the Migration Act to cancel Djokovic’s visa “on health and good order grounds, on the basis that it was in the public interest to do so”.

This is still only half of the story. 
- You never mentioned that 25 other players, team members and officials applied for medical exemptions which were clearly and obviously offered. They were granted to a few (Sasa Ozmo claimed it was nine). So, it was not the case of one player asking a privileged treatment, it was following the rules to a T. 
- Novak missed the ATP Cup taking place in Sydney precisely because he didn't have the medical exemption at the time. Serbia won the ATP Cup two years ago and playing for his country is a top priority for Novak. He would never miss such a tournament. He played Davis Cup a few weeks before that. In an interview yesterday, he said he was ready not to go to Australia at all and is now ready to miss all the tournaments that require the vaccine mandate. 
- Not mentioning being in Spain on a declaration, was an honest mistake. The pictures of him practicing there were all over the social media and there was really nothing to be gained by withdrawing that information. In fact, at his boarding in Dubai, the same question was asked and he himself responded in the affirmative. Making a fuss about omitting it is just muddying the waters. 
- During the first court session, judge Kelly asked: "What more could this man have done?" implying that he had everything in order. The ruling of the second hearing confirmed that all his documents and paperwork was valid. Let me remind others, those few who received medical exemptions were already in Melbourne, some for more than a week, practicing and going about their business. Renata Voracova even took part in a warm up tournament. Only after the mishandling of Djokovic case, she was placed in the same shabby hotel, interrogated for hours, ordered to undress... Croatian coach Filip Serdarusic couldn't follow his brother to  a challenger tournament that they were about to travel to from Melbourne. Lines person didn't even wait to be approached, she left immediately on her own. None of them would have been expelled had it not been for mistreatment of Novak. 
- Novak's Instagram post saying that he got the exemption made the Australians crazy after the brutal lock downs that were imposed on them. Sydney Morning Herald reported: 
"Former Australian Open tournament director Paul McNamee was left stunned that Djokovic would be the only Australian Open participant so far to have his visa approved and then rejected.
“For those asking, all players go through the same visa process overseen by Tennis Australia to play the Australian Open [as non Australians are currently not able to enter]. So it beggars belief that Djokovic is the only player that has had his visa granted and then rescinded,” McNamee said on Twitter. 
On Wednesday, the former doubles champion said: “We need to remember one thing … even if you are angry, Novak Djokovic did not set the rules.” "
That anger prompted even Jaala Pulford to say she hoped Nadal would win which was a pretty ugly statement considering all the other players in the draw.
- While in detention, Novak didn't have change of clothes. He was guarded by two policemen. His diplomatic passport was taken as well as all his possessions. This is how a government could potentially treat illegal immigrants, not those who had all the documents in order and who would never attempt an illegal entry. Also, Nole would never embark on a 25 hour flight just so he could try his luck at the border. 

After the first week, AO had losses. More people were looking at how to get the refund than how to get tickets. More than 20 players and team members were positive while taking part in the tournament. Vaccinated Rublev entered Australia positive. Talking about protecting the borders... Bernard Tomic played sick as well as Ugo Humbert. In the end, the fear of what Novak's presence might incite (totally ridiculous specially considering Australia has about 93% of vaccinated population) was offered as a reason for his visa being cancelled. To quote The Age:
"Australian Lawyers Alliance spokesman Greg Barns SC, a barrister experienced in migration cases, said Djokovic was now feeling the full force of migration laws designed to remove suspected terrorists from Australia, not tennis players.

“One of the most dangerous aspects of the Djokovic matter is the preparedness of the federal government to deem someone to be a risk to public order simply on the basis of what it perceives that person’s views might be,” Mr Barns said. “This is Orwellian and it is deeply troubling in a society supposedly committed to freedom of speech and freedom of thought.”

Let's be 100% honest here, from a man to another man, Novak Djokovic was deported because of political motives. He was not deported because he had the wrong passport, visa or medical exemption, since he had all the necessary documents to travel from Spain to the UAE (Dubai) and from the UAE to Australia. No person gets on a plane without the necessary travel documents. Even Judge Anthony Kelly determined that Djokovic had all the legal arguments to play tennis in Victoria, Australia... 

This was a witch hunt from the Australian federal government, to gain votes with an upcoming election in May (that they probably won't win), and the Western media, who have prosecuted Djokovic since he rejected Great Britain's offer to represent their country in 2006. Just look at the way CNN got rid of Ben Rothenberg recently, the main journalist responsible for spreading so many lies on Djokovic (especially last January). The media has been exposed big time and Australian authorities have become the laughingstock of the globe (unless Canada keeps doing its thing). 

Regardless of your views on vaccination or public health, we should not celebrate an athlete, one of the healthiest human beings on the planet, who has already had COVID TWICE (most recently in December 2021), being deported after being held hostage in a refugee hotel, and the authorities justifying it with "he can spread anti-vaccination sentiment." What has the world become? When did we lose our sense of freedom? Since when do we all blindly follow authorities that have failed to promote our freedom since 2020? Do we really need to make a successful, honorable person, who has given happiness and donations to the rest of the world before, look like a clown because we need to promote our agendas? The worst part is most of the planet celebrated this deportation in the name of "respecting rules," and a specific toxic fanbase celebrated because they wanted their idol to win the Australian Open after 13 years... 

Overall, this situation sucks for Djokovic because he probably would have beaten Nadal in the semifinal in straight sets (Nadal has not won a set against him on hard courts since 2013), and in the final vs Medvedev we will never know... It is what it is. Remember that God sees everything, and Novak Djokovic will get the last laugh eventually :-)
